⁰ Aristotle does not recognise this account of matteras understood in every qnare proposition, hut only as repressori in a nwdol. (see above, p. 37.) In the latter case it is no test of quantity, aethere are universal and particular propositione of each mode. The distinction in the text, however, seems to have been early introduced. Itis implied in the commentary of Ammonius on de Int. 7. (Scholia, p. 115. a. 14.) And Psellus defines the three kinds of matter thus: Necessory, when the predicate isos the cesenae, or a property ; continyent when it is an accident to the subject ; impossible, when a repugnant quality.¹ In this he is followed by Petrus Hispanus. But this consideration of matter is clearly extralogical. See Sir W. Hamilton, Ed. Rev. No, 115. p. 217. The Leonico cannot determine a proposition to be necessary or contingent, unless statedassuch. The pointmust be ascertained from the Science to which the proposition materially belongs. The Logician, however, may use indefinitas as particidars, not assigning a quantity from the matter, but admitting an indefinite premise (and therefore conclusion) where the rules of the figure do not require an universal. Hence the minor premise in fig. 1. may be indefinite, but not the major. See An. Pr. i. 4. 9.
